The API Gateway setup is **complete and correctly wired**. All five required resources are present in `terraform/modules/lambda/main.tf`:

| Resource | Status |
|----------|--------|
| `aws_apigatewayv2_api` (HTTP API) | present |
| `aws_apigatewayv2_integration` (`AWS_PROXY` → Lambda) | present |
| `aws_apigatewayv2_route` (`POST /events`) | present |
| `aws_apigatewayv2_stage` (`$default`, `auto_deploy = true`) | present |
| `aws_lambda_permission` (allows APIGW to invoke Lambda) | present |

The `source_arn` on the permission (`execution_arn}/*/*/events`) correctly scopes to any stage/method on the `/events` path, and the `api_gateway_url` output at `modules/lambda/outputs.tf:14` appends `/events` to the stage invoke URL — so callers get the full usable URL.

**What will break end-to-end (not API Gateway, but Lambda):**

The Lambda IAM role only has `AWSLambdaBasicExecutionRole` (CloudWatch Logs). The handler tries to write to S3 but there is no `s3:PutObject` policy attached. The API Gateway will invoke the Lambda successfully, but the Lambda itself will fail with an `AccessDenied` error when calling `s3.put_object`.

To fix it, add an inline policy to `terraform/modules/lambda/main.tf` under the IAM role:

```hcl
resource "aws_iam_role_policy" "s3_write" {
  name = "${var.lambda_name}-s3-write"
  role = aws_iam_role.lambda_exec.id

  policy = jsonencode({
    Version = "2012-10-17"
    Statement = [{
      Effect   = "Allow"
      Action   = "s3:PutObject"
      Resource = "arn:aws:s3:::${var.bucket_name}/events/*"
    }]
  })
}
```

